'''Takeminakata Tomi no Mikoto Hikokamiwake Shrine''' (健御名方富命彦神別神社, ''Takeminakata Tomi no Mikoto Hikokamiwake Jinja'') is a shrine located in {{ill|Nagano City|ja|長野市}}, {{ill|Nagano Prefecture|ja|長野県}}, Japan. The shrine is listed as a {{ill|Shikinaisha|ja|式内社}}, specifically a {{ill|Myōjin Taisha|ja|名神大社}}, although its status remains disputed among scholars. Under the {{ill|Modern System of Ranked Shinto Shrines|ja|近代社格制度}}, it held the rank of a prefectural shrine.

The shrine is also known colloquially as "Shiroyama Prefectural Shrine," "Minouchi Taisha," and "Hikokamiwake Shrine."

== Overview ==
[[File:Yokoyamajyo.jpg|thumb|220px|right|Torii<br/>Inscription "Takeminakata Tomi no Mikoto Hikokamiwake Shrine" by Prince Arisugawa Taruhito]]
The shrine is located in {{ill|Shiroyama Park (Nagano)|ja|城山公園 (長野市)}}, within the ruins of {{ill|Yokoyama Castle (Shinano Province)|ja|横山城 (信濃国)}} and adjacent to the east of {{ill|Zenkoji|ja|善光寺}}. It was originally situated north of Zenkoji’s main hall as "Toshigami-dō" (Year God Hall), serving as a protective shrine for Zenkoji. During the {{ill|Shinbutsu Bunri|ja|神仏分離}} movement at the beginning of the Meiji period, it was relocated to its current location.

The shrine enshrines {{ill|Takeminakata|ja|建御名方神|lt=Takeminakata Tomi no Mikoto}}, the same deity worshipped at {{ill|Suwa Taisha|ja|諏訪大社}}. On its grounds, {{ill|Onbashira|ja|御柱}} are erected, and the shrine participates in the {{ill|O
